segments.text: apparent to the former student's board that we just had to raise some money.
We were not, we didn't have much of a staff, so we just had Lonnie Locke and the secretary were keeping all the books, and he was doing the student loans, see?
And the scholarship work was being done over at the, well it didn't have a student aid office, heck, it was being done up in the
No, I guess we were doing everything there in former students.
And then when we got a development, when McQuillan moved, then he took the Opportunity Award scholarships with him to the development office.
I think there was a guy named Morgan.
I'm a little bit hazy right in here as to when McQuillan went.
Oh, that's it.
In 47, McQuillan, when Dick Hervey came, he took the Opportunity Award Scholarship program and all.
He did not take student loans.
Anyway, there was Dick Hervey in the secretary.
There was a records lady and an assistant.
And there was Mrs. Shepherd by herself.
And then there was a part-time English prof, Elmquist.
Aggie was a tabloid printed by the press, and it was late all the time of the month.
And then we had three people in the mailroom.
And one was an Aggie wife, and the other two were students.
And Pinky Downs' desk.
Old Pinky.
You remember him?
Yeah.
Anyway, so.
And where was all this housed?
It was housed in the west end, on the first floor west end of the MSC.
When we remodeled it, and we used the back entrance and the mailroom entrance,

was the fire escape and when we had to be careful to not clog up that fire escape hall fire chief and just eat our ass out and say well don't you said people couldn't get out of this place you got to keep that empty don't you can use it yeah right but we had we had a crash door thing on it from the inside and so we can put a glass door on it so you can anyway
But it became apparent.
So they said, what we need to do is one A&M man ask another one to give.
We need to have personal solicitation.
Well, they didn't quite know how to get it kicked off.
So Dick called me and he said, I remember you telling me that you did United Fund.
I said, that's right.
I was downtown chairman.
I was building chairman, the various chairman of these districts for the United Fund.
And I had my own company, which was City Public Service.
And we had a lot of employees.
So I got someone at each power plant and electric distribution to take cards.
And it was pretty easy to do.
The boss of the company said, I give so much, I'll expect all employees to give something.
Ideally, you'd give a certain .
Boy, people didn't like that much to be told they had to give.
But they did.
And so I learned at least organization.
Then I got in on the solicitation of our church.
We started a new church, Jefferson Methodist Church.
And I was involved in that.
program of capital giving as well as the annual giving for the church budget.
So being on these fundraising committees involved, I had a sense of what I could do.
And so the only breakdown they could give me was San Antonio, and they could give me class years, and that's it.
They could give me county.
We had these tabs.
See, we had address graph plates.
So we had a tab up there for giving, a tab up there for class year, and a tab up there for county and city.
And so we could break the cards out about like that.
Oh, yeah, major course of study.
No, colleges, College of Education, Engineering, or Liberal Arts, and so on.
We had those tabs.
We had eight tabs, I think, across the top of those addressograph plates.
And it was a pretty primitive system up to a hair foot.
Compared to what you can do with a computer.
Oh, well, anyway.
I think I've seen that old addressograph machine or one like it around here somewhere.
Yeah, it makes me sick.
So the fun of it is we knew we had to do something about upgrading the whole thing.
We also had to upgrade programs and so on.
So what they did, they had a good long-range study.
And out of this study came, we had to do personal solicitations.
We had to.
And this study was within the former students?
Within the former students, yeah.
Long range study.
Yeah.
Yeah.
It's still, Randy Metz still got it in file over there.
I hope he's got it Xeroxed and preserved for prosperity.
Anyway, and this, we had to have a better publication.
We had, well, all this reflected programs, staff, personal solicitation, and all these.
This took staff.
Mm-hmm.
So obviously we had to do something, because at this time I had gone with Sharpen Company and was traveling all the time.
So I had a little time that I could figure out this stuff.
So Dick said, why don't I do some experiments?

So we got together and designed a jacket and a little envelope to put our workers' cards in and put a little campaign material about why we needed the annual fund, what the projects were, and so on, and to give to workers.
Dick went ahead and we did an experiment in 1959.
We had it all finished, and he sent me the cards on San Antonio for the ones who'd given and the ones that hadn't given in the last year.

And I was able to break them down by a major course of study as far as engineering, agriculture, liberal arts, and science, and medicine, and so on, the various schools, you know, that we could tab at a different level, tab in there.
So man, you're working in the San Antonio area.
So I devised this system.
I said, OK, I'll get the lawyers.
See, I knew everybody.
So I get the lawyers and the doctors, dentists, insurance men, and then my company, Aggies with Public Service Board, Aggies with Texaco, Shell, and so on.
Then I had the class agents.
I had some class agents there in town.
And I got them.
I said, now, Henry, you're the class of 16.
How about taking your cards?
Oh, you bet.
And of course, our motto then was not the amount of your gift, but you are the important gift.
See, we wanted a $10 gift.
A $25 gift was cause for celebration.
A $5 gift was common, and a $10 gift was about average.
Actually, our average.
gift at the end of that year was $12.81.
We were shook up and said, we can't do it on this.
What are we going to do?
So I started traveling around the country, going to these American Alumni Council meetings and so on.
Wait, I'm getting ahead of myself.
So anyway, it was determined that I did this.
Boy, listen, our percentage of participation jumped way up.
We jumped up to almost 70%, 68% participation.
in giving, but our average gift was $10.
That's what I'm trying to say.
So when we had a board meeting and I presented what we'd done on this personal solicitation, well, that's the way to go.
We've got to get them involved.
Then after we get them involved, then we'll talk about amount.
Let's get them giving.
And after we get them giving, but then we've got to have a good publication.
We didn't have that Texas Aggie tabloid.
It was terrible.
And so what are we going to do about that?
Well, it's going to take money, because then you've got to get a full-time editor.
Carl Elkiss was teaching regular load in English in the English department.
So what in the world were we going to do?
Well, we just had to have additional staff.
So they decided it was going to be me.
I didn't know this, but I guess it was 1960, Earl Rudder and Dick Hervey called me up to Bandera.
Past presidents were having a meeting.
And here Dick Hervey and Earl Rudder take me back in the Purple Sage Motel.

and told me that they wanted me to move to College Station to take over the annual giving program, be the assistant executive director, and be in charge of clubs and activities, club activities, and annual giving.
Prepare direct mail pieces.
which I had a pretty good perspective of because of the advertising thing that I had.
That really helped.
And I found out about Jim Earl right away and got him to be my artist.
And all he won was, well, at the time I got him it was Century Club, so I gave him the Century Club credit for doing my artwork.
Who was that?
Jim Earl.
Jim Earl, yeah.
He was a graduate student at the time.
Incidentally, I'm going to ask Jim Earl to do a plate.
for this revised book of Cadet Slouch with some kind of cover.
I thought he was wonderful, too.
I hated to see him go, you know?
You don't have to go and pay any attention to him anymore.
He'd be well to death.
Oh, I liked him.
In fact, you let me know what it is.
I'll take him to lunch or dinner or something and get him to do it.
No, I've already asked.
He said he'd be delighted to do it.
Great.
And I asked him to kind of write me sort of an epilogue about Cadet Slouch.
Beautiful.
Yeah, I think it'll be amazing.
So anyway, I told him, I said,
I said, did you check my transcript?
Earl said, uh-huh.
He said, I won't check yours if you won't check mine.
Come on, we've taken the same thing industrialized.
So anyway, Earl said, he said, I was in his division.
I was in the reserve.
I was the lieutenant colonel.
I was commanding a battalion.
I was commanding the armored cavalry reconnaissance squadron in the 90th infantry division.
He said,
It was a recon outfit, you know, armored stuff.
I got that from Fort Knox when I was on the staff instructor up there for a while during the Korea thing.
That's why I didn't go overseas, because I stayed in school all the time.
I went to the Air Ground Operations School.
I forgot that one.
Went to the Engineering School.
Went to nothing but school during that time.
I bet you the Army's got a million dollars in education.
I went to Command General Staff School for a year or so.
You were a professional soldier there.
That's right, that's right.
Exactly.
You got it.
And I had a pretty good rank, you know.
So I went home and told my family.
I said, President Rudder and Mr. Hervey, Hervey authorized it from the board because I had the experience.
I'd done this.
I had the track record, and I wasn't even on the staff.
See, I was a volunteer.
So that's what got me the job right there.
So I came back and told the kids.
I said, we're going to move to College Station.
And I'm going to move.

in april next year 61 and y'all are going to move in september we'll take this time to sell a house take me to find a house but uh we'll move labor day and that'll get you up there and go oh i'm not going to leave they started crying and you're here claire didn't want to leave her gorgeous house and all kind of stuff and i said well it's like moving to the church when we moved over when my stepfather gave us this house and i gave him my house we traded out
He sold mine.
He couldn't sell.
This big old house was on San Pedro, Highway 281.
Anyway, I said, I'm going to move to College Station, and I hope you all will come with me.
I said, if you don't, that's fine.
I'll send you rent money for a checkup.
So during the summer, I commuted.
And I went home every Friday evening, and I came back every Sunday evening.
That was all we did, except we did take a trip.
We went to a convention in Miami, Florida, and Claire went with us.
That's over.
She met all these people.
I was going to ask you about the stress and the strain.
Well, that cost a lot.
But anyway, we went to Miami, Florida, and we had a ball.
We took a trip to Nassau afterwards and so on.
McClellan, six of us, in a 61 Oldsmobile, McClellan, Hervey's, and Weir's in the car.
The first thing
People were smoking.
And I said, well, folks, we can't smoke in this car.
One person at a time that cracked the window.
We made Julia McQuillan the smoke officer.
Smoke control officer.
So anyway, so by the time the summer was over, Claire and the kids were up.
It's a good thing we did, because they're here.
They really fit in beautifully.
They both achieved a lot here.
They did well.
They both graduated from college, one Texas and one North Texas music.
So it was a great thing we did.
I'm glad it worked.
But imagine here, I was 40 years old starting a whole new career.
You really had a multifaceted career.
I didn't realize you'd done all those things.
Just fantastic.
And so I learned a lot.
You are a full-time employee at this point of the Former Students Association.
Your check came from the Former Students Association.
I wasn't making quite as much as I was making before, but of course that was commissions and I
I could have made twice that much if I'd worked twice that hard when you're a salesman.
But I was really lucky.
I was lucky I had a good boss.
But anyway, I came to work up here with more money than McClellan was making.
He went over as director of development, say, in 1947, when Dick came.
Anyway, at that time, we're still making student loans and doing all this stuff.
I figured this has got to stop.
We've got to have a full-time, big student financial aid office.
Well, see, Runner was big on faculty and scientists.
He would pay, and we raised money to supplement their salaries until they could get enough research and whatever else money, salaries.
We got five or six people.
We really, when he got senior and buyers and all these reals, and all those people who were National Academy people,
what do you call them, the Nobel Prize winners.
Well, they cost a lot of money.
And we paid for the moving expenses.
So let's go back in.
So I came here.
And the first thing I did when I got here was change a whole direct mail appeal.
And I had some ideas from San Antonio, from advertising.
I was in the advertising club there.
So I got a lot of my friends in the advertising agency business and artwork business to give me ideas.
Plus, I looked at annual giving appeals from other schools, which I didn't really like because they didn't fit Aggies.
I tried to fit mine to A&M people.
Who did you look at?
Who was doing good in gift raising in those days?
What universities were you going to?
You have to realize this.
Most of the schools, I'd say that 99% of all the universities in America, alumni associations, have dues.
Giving, annual giving, is done by development.
But we didn't have any development.
So we called our annual giving the development fund of the former student association.
We had a development foundation that Herman Heath and Doc Doherty had set up, but it was dormant.
Until Dorsey McCrory went over to that, there wasn't even anybody looking after it, see?
We didn't have anybody moving that.
We just had an endowment sitting over there.
The income went to the discretion of the former students board.
We gave it to the university.
We just gave it to the president.
It was out of our budget, but we gave him the money.
Because we had former student trustees.
We appointed the trustees, the former students, but we still do, to the development foundation.
That's why we locked together.
And all that's out of the control of the university, fiscal.
We give them money, but they don't raise it.
We raise it and give it to them.
So I had nothing to go by on annual giving to alumni association, except one, University of Pennsylvania.
Is that right?
How did you pick up on them?
Well, I'll tell you.
I went to these annual meetings, and I talked to everybody.
And we had annual giving meetings, and we had a dog.
The annual giving was always in development.
But Ohio State was pretty close.
Their alumni and development was together.
Well, their development had a century club.
But that money did not go to the alumni.
Yet they were housed in the same building.
It would be like our building, William's building, had half development on one side and half alumni on the other side.
And so Kenyon Campbell was the guy of development.
And I can't remember the other guy's name.
He was with alumni.
He was a feisty.
Kept them out of the Rose Bowl and all that kind of stuff.
Anyway, I couldn't find anybody that had, Texas Tech and those schools had dues, and University of Texas had dues, they had lifetime memberships and that sort of stuff.
So here we would have annual giving, but our average gift was about the same as dues.
I knew we had to do something.
So I got the idea from Ohio State.
But that was development.
But then I found, when I went to that meeting up at the Big Ten, there was a guy from the University of Pennsylvania there, and he had what he called the Ben Franklin Associates.
Other schools I looked at, Oklahoma or, say, Purdue or all those others, if they had like the John Purdue Club, that was all for football.
That was like our hanging club for 12 men and five.
So the John Purdue Club was for football.
$100 a year for football.
No priority tickets and so on.
So at the University of Pennsylvania, Ben Franks Olsen was annual giving to the alumni.
Their development went for bigger stuff than that.
But they knew that if their alumni were going to function, they had to.
So I said, that's it.
So with the Century Club idea from Ohio State and the annual giving from the University of Pennsylvania, I found it.
And I came back and I prepared.
the paper to the board.
And we met down at Tenneco, and I presented it to them.
There's a century club, $100.
And then I said, we should have other levels.
But we didn't quite know what to call those things.
Well, they said, first of all, let's go to $100 right now.
Don't worry about the higher level.
They approved it.
Whenever the time comes, go ahead and prove it.
We didn't know what to call it.
I couldn't think of the names of things like that.
I didn't come up with the 12th Man Foundation, see.
I knew that was a bad name.
I mean the Aggie Club was a bad name.
So we came up and I presented Century Club certificates.
Big mailing went out to all the people who had given to the
Anybody who gave to the stadium expansion, we gave them Century Club credit, see?
I said, Royce, that's restricted giving.
He said, that's right, but next year, we'll send a little tab along to hang on the bottom.
Next year, it won't be restricted, see?
And it worked.
Over half of them kept giving $100, see?
So we started out with probably 2,000 people giving $100 a year, just like that.
Just like that.
That's an incredible success.
So I was in power one day.
And it tied into the stadium expansion.
Yeah.
In what year?
No, well, it was when, see, these people bought options in the old press box expansion that Bowles Urban did.
Yeah, yeah.
And then when we built the deck on it in 66, 65?
Must have been, I bet, 65.
Okay, I was trying to think.
Because my plaque says 68, and that's when we finished it.
I got a plaque in there on my stadium.
We had to do that, too.
We didn't have a 12-month Aggie club or anybody with us to do that.
So here the former students are doing all these other damn things.
But Weisenbaker said, I'll tell you about Weisenbaker here in a minute.
because he's tied into a lot of this stuff, like the President Scholars and so on.

Anyway, so, I'm sitting in Weisenbaker's office, and we're gloating over the success of the Central Club, and I said, look, what we're doing here is kind of a Mickey Mouse printed certificate we're sending people.
And I said, it's not, it doesn't have any oomph to it.
It doesn't have pizzazz.
And I said, you know, I still had that advertising stuff in me.
My whole background really fitted me for this job.
It was quite unusual that I learned the United Front thing and church thing and advertising.
So anyway, I'm sitting and looking up at the wall, and there it was.
The YMCA Century Club with a gorgeous casting of a boy's head.
And when I looked at that, I saw the University seal instead of the boy's head.
I saw Century Club written below it.
I got one on the wall right there, one of the first ones.
And so that was the logo and the billboard there.
And I said, Royce, can we call that YMCA man here?
He said, hey, sir, call old so-and-so at the YMCA and have him.
We want to talk to him.
So I got him on the phone.
I talked to him.
I said, I'm in Mr. Weisenbaker's office, and I'm looking at your plaque.
And I noticed on the back of it, it said the Sports Award Company of Chicago.
Are you still doing business with them?
He said, yeah.
How much do these cost?
He said, $10.
I said, OK. $10 a piece?
And so I said, oh, man.
And so I said, well, that's fine.
Thank you very much.
I took their address down and everything else.
And phone number.
He had the phone number, too.
I plan to use a similar award, if I can raise the money, to buy these plaques.
Because they'll really go over big, I think.
And I said, you don't mind if I?
Oh, no.
He said, that's fine.
It's public information.
He said, I hope you're successful.
Because I said, he says, they won't always say YMCA.
So to see how it'd go, I figured, why don't we buy 1,000 to start with?
And so I said, what in the world are we going to do?
for money, and I said, well, I think I'll call executive committee meeting, and then if I need a board meeting, we'd just have to appropriate some money.
We're going to have to find $10,000 somewhere.
I think it was $7,500 plus the postage, plus the cost of the casting, plus the artwork and that sort of thing.
But you have to make ready to produce these plaques.
I think we needed about $10,000 all together.
I think the plaques really were $750 apiece.
That was about right.
It turned out about $10 round figures.
Packaging and mailing and all that stuff.

issue right old buck a $10,000 check to the former students association he said I'm sitting there and I want to jump across the desk and kiss it I want to say I love you you're the greatest man in the world so see that old fundraisers when something like that happens we go all to pieces we want to shout to the skies and hit the ceiling so she came in with a $10,000 check made out to the former students and I raced back to
down here, and we got Tom around to do the artwork.
He was at the press then.
We didn't get Tom for quite a while.
And we did the details of what we wanted the plaque to say, the little plate that's on it, and then the other, the year tabs below it.
I go ahead, Dave says, I got that plaque, and I thought to myself, the minute I saw those little hooks on the bottom, I said, uh-oh.
Oh, shit.
He said, the goddamn virus has got me again.
That's good.
So that's a good story.
That started that, and we nailed those plaques out to the... And they first went out wind, you know?
Roughly.
66, yeah.
Because we gave anybody credit for being a founding member of 65 or 66 if they gave an either here and the gifts to the stadium expansion.
Now, this is a $100 gift that's getting you that plaque.
A $100 gift.
And anyway, here you send the plaque out.
We just started converting to magazine.
We really didn't have an editor yet.
Yeah, we did.
We got an editor in 66.
Well, see, as soon as the money started coming in, I could hire somebody.
See, there's no state money.
We're sitting over there having to use that gift money as everything we get.
And boy, that's why it took me a while to get our personnel classified as the same as state.
For example, I had to get my people classified somehow.
And we didn't have benefits equal to the state or anything.
So it took me a while to get.
So finally, when Juanita Murray came after Lonnie Locke retired,
We got everybody in the place classified according to the state pay scale.
Personnel gave me all the state classifications for various editors and accountants and secretaries.
And we were able to classify every one of our people the same as the university.
And with the experience, we had the steps, the step one, two, four, or something like that.
I should know this, but is the Former Students Association is chartered or organized as what?
As a philanthropic or?
Philanthropic Edomocenary Association classified
The charter is under the Secretary of State, State of Texas, 99-year thing.
When was that charter?
I know when the former singers began and all that stuff, but the charter really was probably written?
It's in John Adams' book or something.
Back in the 30s, 20s, maybe 21?
Yeah, that sounds about right.
21, 100-year charter, 99-year charter, Secretary of State.
And then in 1940, 41, we've got one of the first March of Dimes, 501C3 philanthropic organization.
See, the March of Dimes charter was the first one under Roosevelt.
When would that be, 1940, 39?
Yeah, right in there.
So we had a guy named Ted Moley, and he got the
Former students were one of the first ones that got that tax-exempt, philanthropic, all those words they use in their letter from IRS, which you have to renew every so many years.
You have to apply for a new.
Then we got one, see, we got one for the for the Aggie Club.
And we had one for the Development Foundation.
We had all three of those were chartered by the state and by the federal government as charitable.
organizations for the 501 tax code.
So that's the beginning, really, of your successful fundraising is the Century Club plaque.
Right.
That plaque did it.
See, we took pictures of it.
We had pictures of it in the magazine.
We had pictures of it everywhere.
See, my first full-time editor was Joe Buser.
And Joe Buser had just come back from the service.
I think I got him in 67.
Elnquist tried a large, oversized, and we took the tabloid and tried to make a magazine out of it.
It didn't work too well.
We had to get a full-time editor, and we had to go commercial so we could get time set, and a printing done, and a commercial operation to get it out on time.
And in the press, we had a low priority.

That's when I was convinced the way we were treated by different agencies on the campus, putting off, well, we'll do that tomorrow, you know, the inefficiencies of it, no motivational sense of purpose or no sense of urgency.
And I said, well, we've got to computerize.
We'll do it with data processing, but we're going to control the records.
The university will not control these records.
He said, how could I ever get a mailing list?
I'd have to go on low priority, like these other schools, like LSU.
I got them off of the statement.
So that was their hang-up.
Well, almost all these schools, SMU, all these alumni associations.
Well, they start out because they think it saves them money, and it ends up throttling them.
The University of Texas.
They have their own record system, but the university pays them for keeping the addresses of alumni.
Our registrar actually can get money to keep alumni records, but our people won't.
Our formal student payers are just so viciously independent.
They don't want to depend on the university.
Are you chilly?
No, I'm fine.
Thank you.
I can turn it.
And we got a lot, I didn't realize we had so much to say.
And I wonder where you are.
I'll come back if you get tired.
So, the Century Club.

Then, when Bob Latimer was president a couple years later, I can't remember the year, I've got it, we're in his house and after the second martini, maybe it was while we were drinking the second martini, I said, Bob,
One thing we've got to do this year, his company had been sold and he was kept on salary, good big salary for a year.

And so he was present for it and all he did then was get invested in the magazine and I had to fire an editor and hire, I think I had to fire a guy and I hired, I guess that's when we hired Jerry Cooper.
And I said we've got to get this upper level, Central Club going better.
I said we've got to identify and give a name to these levels.
And I said, well what can we do?
We were talking about the cum laude level, and I said well I was going to tie it in with academia, you know.
And little old Jane Lyons says, well why don't you just call it like precious metals, like gold and silver and brass and so on.
And I said, oh that's great, okay, it'll be silver for $250 and it'll be $500 for the
golden for the $500, and then what in the world are we going to call that top one, the $1,000?
She said, oh, that's easy.
Call that the diamond.
I said, God, gee, you're just wonderful.
So she's the one that made the...
So then we kicked that off in good shape, and boy, it was really successful.
So now they got the double diamond.
Now they got them endowed, see, and everything.
Then we started being able to get staff.
Then I could hire a field director, and I hired...
an associate.
That's when I got Bob Walker as a developer.
But see, what happened there?
Let me tell you what happened to Bob Walker.
Instead of him coming and taking over my job as field and all the other kind of stuff, we had kicked off the presidency.
The board of directors in 1966, we'll say, or 7, authorized
the President's Scholars Program.
That was gifts.
Yeah, I remember that.
We had to get gifts, or the Board of Regents had to appropriate the money for these President's Scholars.
We were trying to get the Brady kids, you know.
And I don't know how many we had, not many, probably 10.
So the former students had worked with the Regents, and so we were pledged to fund so many, too.
So the Regents funded some, and we funded the rest.
I think we were funding about,
I think there probably were 20 or 25 altogether.
We were funding half each.
And then Wisemaker came up with the idea, shit, let's endow these.
$25,000 endowment.
They got together and worked out the interest rates and so on.
And the Board of Regents, and we said, give us permission to go and work these endowments, and we'll get going.
Well, I got the artwork done.
I got the letter written to Rudder and all the stuff, a real fancy package to send to people to get this $25,000 gift.
